  <div id="home">
   <div class="w3-row w3-padding-0">
    <div class="w3-twothird w3-container">
      <p> br <br> </p>
      <h1 class="w3-text-brown">Religion and Beliefs</h1> 
      <p>Traditionally, the Kadazan-Dusun practiced animism, believing in the presence of spirits in nature and ancestral guidance. Their worldview was deeply tied to their environment, with sacred rituals performed to honor spirits associated with the land, water, and skies. Central to their spiritual practices is the Bobohizan, a highly respected priestess or shaman who acts as an intermediary between the physical and spiritual worlds.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="w3-third w3-container"> <div id="4.1">
      <p> br <br> </p>
      <img src="https://sph.dailyexpress.com.my/archive/uploads/firstritual17.jpg" alt="Kadazandusun Ceremony" style="width:270px;height:270px;">
    </div> 
  </div> 

  
   <div class="w3-row"> 
    <div class="w3-twothird w3-container"> 
      <h3 class="w3-text-brown">4.1</h3> 
      <p>One of the most significant beliefs revolves around Huminodun, the rice spirit. According to legend, Huminodun sacrificed herself to bring life to the Kadazan-Dusun people, and rice is seen as her embodiment. This belief underpins the Pesta Kaamatan, where rituals are performed to express gratitude for the harvest and to seek blessings for future prosperity. Such practices demonstrate the community's deep reverence for sustenance and life.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="w3-third w3-container"> <div id="4.2"> 
      <img src="https://sabahtourism.com/assets/uploads/RS27769_No.20-A%C2%A9-Sabah-Tourism_Tsen-Lip-Kai.jpg" alt="Pesta Kaamatan" style="width:270px;height:200px;">
    </div>
  </div>

   <div class="w3-row">                                  
 <div class="w3-twothird w3-container"> 
      <h3 class="w3-text-brown">4.2</h3> 
      <p>The arrival of Christianity and Islam in Sabah during the colonial era and through trade brought significant changes to Kadazan-Dusun religious practices. Today, the majority of Kadazan-Dusun identify as Christians, particularly Roman Catholics, while a smaller number follow Islam. Despite these shifts, elements of traditional beliefs remain woven into their religious practices and rituals, reflecting a blending of old and new.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="w3-third w3-container"> <div id="4.3">
      <img src="https://www.catholicadkk.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/kd-audio-bible.jpg" alt="Kadazandusun Christian" style="width:270px;height:200px;">
    </div>
  </div>

      
    <div class="w3-twothird w3-container">
      <h3 class="w3-text-brown">4.3</h3> 
      <p>Modern religious practices coexist with traditional ceremonies in many Kadazan-Dusun communities. For instance, during weddings or harvest celebrations, it is not uncommon for both Christian prayers and traditional blessings to be performed. This syncretism highlights the adaptability of the Kadazan-Dusun in maintaining their heritage while embracing new beliefs.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="w3-third w3-container">
      <img src="https://www.heraldmalaysia.com/uploads/news/2016/5/7561951821462265544.jpg" alt="Kadazandusun" style="width:270px;height:200px;"> <div id="4.4"> 
    </div>
  </div>
 
   
    <div class="w3-twothird w3-container">
      <h3 class="w3-text-brown">4.4</h3> 
      <p>Efforts to preserve traditional spiritual practices are ongoing, particularly as younger generations become more urbanized and distanced from rural customs. The role of the Bobohizan, once central to the community, has diminished over time, but cultural revivals and educational programs aim to ensure that this vital aspect of Kadazan-Dusun heritage is not forgotten.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="w3-third w3-container">
      <img src="https://assets.nst.com.my/images/articles/kadazandusun_1660816621.jpg" alt="Kadazandusun" style="width:270px;height:210px;">
    </div>
  </div>

